data.content:
MSTest has `CollectionAssert` and more specific assert methods that give **better failure messages** than `Assert.IsTrue`. Here's the improved version:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Use Assert.AreEqual for exact counts — shows expected vs actual on failure
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Use CollectionAssert for collection-level checks
    CollectionAssert.AllItemsAreNotNull(users);

    // Use Assert.IsTrue with a message for predicate checks
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Use Assert.IsNotNull instead of != null
    var admin = users.SingleOrDefault(u => u.Role == "Admin");
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin, "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, count)` | Shows `Expected:3 Actual:0` instead of just `False` |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent and message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(a == b)` | `Assert.AreEqual(a, b)` | Shows both values on failure |
| manual loops | `CollectionAssert.*` | Purpose-built for collections |

**Other useful `CollectionAssert` methods:**
- `Contains(collection, item)` — membership check
- `AreEqual(expected, actual)` — same elements, same order
- `AreEquivalent(expected, actual)` — same elements, **any order**
- `IsSubsetOf(subset, superset)` — subset check

The general rule: pick the **most specific** assert available — it produces the most helpful failure output.
